one of them is bound to be right.

448
00:30:48,380 --> 00:30:51,145
Yeah. He's just
a lucky, lucky guy.

449
00:30:51,216 --> 00:30:55,381
<i>Listen, listen. I just think it wouldn't
hurt him to learn a little humility.</i>

450
00:30:56,521 --> 00:30:58,456
So what's the verdict?

451
00:30:58,523 --> 00:31:02,460
Embolus. The arm problem
was caused by a clot.

452
00:31:02,527 --> 00:31:05,019
<i>There's a good chance we
can bust the clot with T. P.A.</i>

453
00:31:05,097 --> 00:31:08,397
Do it. See what
happens to his arm.

454
00:31:17,542 --> 00:31:20,774
We found a blood
clot in your brain.

455
00:31:20,846 --> 00:31:24,180
We'd like to start you on
heparin. It's a blood thinner.

456
00:31:24,249 --> 00:31:28,744
- What are the side effects?
- Well, your lungs are kind of
chewed up from the pneumonia.

457
00:31:28,820 --> 00:31:31,415
- Good chance there'll be an effusion.
- Bleeding?

458
00:31:31,490 --> 00:31:36,053
Into his lungs. It's our best chance
to give you back the use of your arm.

459
00:31:36,128 --> 00:31:37,858
I don't need my
arm without my air.

460
00:31:37,929 --> 00:31:41,422
- The damage would likely be minimal.
- No.

461
00:31:43,435 --> 00:31:46,030
It's his call.

462
00:31:47,038 --> 00:31:49,769
Or we could do an embolectomy.

463
00:31:49,841 --> 00:31:51,776
Basically, we go in
and pull the clot out.

464
00:31:51,843 --> 00:31:55,780
He's saying no to drugs, and
you're recommending brain surgery?

465
00:31:55,847 --> 00:31:57,839
Bypasses the risk to the lungs.

466
00:31:57,916 --> 00:32:00,078
- It'll either help your
arm, or— - Or it'll kill me.

467
00:32:00,152 --> 00:32:03,884
From your point of
view, it's a win-win.

468
00:32:03,955 --> 00:32:06,254
Okay.

469
00:32:06,324 --> 00:32:09,055
We'll set up the
procedure for today.

470
00:32:20,872 --> 00:32:23,273
We're in your carotid artery.

471
00:32:23,341 --> 00:32:27,210
This is gonna take us all
the way up into your brain.

472
00:32:27,279 --> 00:32:29,441
You all right?

473
00:32:29,514 --> 00:32:31,642
Yes.

474
00:32:37,756 --> 00:32:39,793
<i>The sludge is
blocking the blood flow</i>

475
00:32:39,817 --> 00:32:41,921
<i>to the part of the brain
that controls your arm.</i>

476
00:32:51,570 --> 00:32:54,369
All done. You still okay?

477
00:32:55,740 --> 00:32:57,675
I think so.

478
00:32:58,743 --> 00:33:00,735
<i>I don't know. I guess...</i>

479
00:33:00,812 --> 00:33:04,442
it's just with Dr. Hamilton here,
I-I noticed a difference in styles.

480
00:33:05,517 --> 00:33:08,851
His style involves humility?

481
00:33:08,920 --> 00:33:11,185
Another difference
in our styles...

482
00:33:11,256 --> 00:33:14,317
I don't care much for
apologies. You can go.

483
00:33:14,392 --> 00:33:16,827
I didn't know you were standing
there when I said that, okay?

484
00:33:16,895 --> 00:33:19,922
It was completely rude. Do
you mean genuine humility,

485
00:33:19,998 --> 00:33:22,593
you know, with all the self-doubt
and the self-questioning,

486
00:33:22,667 --> 00:33:26,536
or Hamilton's polite, patronizing,
"Aw, shucks" humility?

487
00:33:26,605 --> 00:33:28,597
You're both excellent
doctors. Thank you.

488
00:33:28,673 --> 00:33:32,940
And humility is an important
quality, especially if you're wrong a lot.

489
00:33:33,011 --> 00:33:34,980
You've been wrong
every step of the way.

490
00:33:40,385 --> 00:33:45,221
Course, when you're right, self-doubt
doesn't help anybody, does it?

491
00:33:50,962 --> 00:33:53,022
We gotta go.

492
00:34:00,906 --> 00:34:03,842
Congratulations, Greg.

493
00:34:03,909 --> 00:34:06,174
Congratulations. Why, Marty?

494
00:34:06,244 --> 00:34:08,406
John woke up. He
can use his arm.

495
00:34:08,480 --> 00:34:10,574
Thank you.

496
00:34:10,649 --> 00:34:13,175
Now, look, I know we've
had our differences,

497
00:34:13,251 --> 00:34:16,415
but I think when a person does
something well, it ought to be recognized.

498
00:34:16,488 --> 00:34:18,423
The phone works.

499
00:34:18,490 --> 00:34:22,393
Next time you want to make me feel
all warm and fuzzy, leave a message.

500
00:34:22,460 --> 00:34:24,895
Don't get me wrong.
I'm overcome with joy.

501
00:34:24,963 --> 00:34:26,591
- Doc.
- Yeah.

502
00:34:26,665 --> 00:34:30,102
- What?
- You just touched my leg.

503
00:34:30,168 --> 00:34:32,603
What, are you gonna
charge me with assault again?

504
00:34:32,671 --> 00:34:35,539
No.

505
00:34:35,607 --> 00:34:38,202
I felt it.

506
00:34:46,351 --> 00:34:49,116
<i>He now has feeling all
the way up to the calf.</i>

507
00:34:49,187 --> 00:34:51,588
This is the way
medicine evolved.

508
00:34:51,656 --> 00:34:53,648
Patients sometimes get better.

509
00:34:53,725 --> 00:34:56,889
You have no idea why, but unless
you give a reason, they won't pay you.

510
00:34:56,962 --> 00:34:59,022
Anybody notice if
there's a full moon?

511
00:34:59,097 --> 00:35:01,157
You're saying he just
spontaneously got better?

512
00:35:01,232 --> 00:35:03,827
No. I'm saying, let's rule out
the lunar god and go from there.

513
00:35:03,902 --> 00:35:05,837
Something he's on is working.

514
00:35:05,904 --> 00:35:09,068
The enzyme replacement protocol
is working, reversing the A.L.S.

515
00:35:09,140 --> 00:35:11,302
The timing doesn't
seem suspicious to you?

516
00:35:11,376 --> 00:35:14,835
Do you think Dr. House'll see it that way,
figure it's his medication doin' the job?

517
00:35:14,913 --> 00:35:17,075
I'm sure he will.

518
00:35:17,148 --> 00:35:20,209
It's one of ours. <i>How do we figure
out which drug is doing the trick?</i>

519
00:35:20,285 --> 00:35:22,345
Easy. We just stop all of them.

520
00:35:22,420 --> 00:35:25,322
- One of those drugs is helping him.
- And the rest...

521
00:35:25,390 --> 00:35:27,252
Steroids, antibiotics,
anti-inflammatories...

522
00:35:27,276 --> 00:35:29,293
They're toxic, if we
leave him on all of them.

523
00:35:29,361 --> 00:35:31,626
- He'll walk again.
- Yeah. To his own funeral.

524
00:35:31,696 --> 00:35:34,291
But if we stop everything,
he'll get worse. <i>True.</i>

525
00:35:34,366 --> 00:35:36,053
We'll add our medications
back one at a time.

526
00:35:36,077 --> 00:35:37,712
When he gets better,
we'll have our answer.

527
00:35:37,736 --> 00:35:41,400
- And if he doesn't get better?
- Then we're in trouble.

528
00:35:41,473 --> 00:35:43,965
Not as much as he is.

529
00:35:44,042 --> 00:35:46,102
But I suppose
that was your point.

530
00:35:48,947 --> 00:35:53,214
I assume you want me to convince Hamilton
to stop his treatments too. Don't care.

531
00:35:53,284 --> 00:35:56,015
At least five of the medications
are a part of his protocol.

532
00:35:56,087 --> 00:35:58,818
If his stuff was helping, the guy
would be playing tennis months ago.

533
00:35:58,890 --> 00:36:01,223
It's <i>our</i> round of
treatment that's helping.

534
00:36:01,292 --> 00:36:04,387
Right. So <i>that's</i>
what you'll stop.

535
00:36:04,462 --> 00:36:06,954
<i>It shouldn't be more
than 15 or 20 minutes.</i>

536
00:36:07,032 --> 00:36:08,775
So your philosophy
is, if they don't want

537
00:36:08,799 --> 00:36:10,867
treatment, they get it
shoved down their throat,

538
00:36:10,935 --> 00:36:14,736
- but if it might cure their paralysis,
whoa, we better slow down.
- Yeah.

539
00:36:14,806 --> 00:36:17,799
Yes, Doctor, I love it. <i>My old
philosophy used to be live and let live.</i>

540
00:36:17,876 --> 00:36:22,644
But I'm taking this needlepoint class,
and they gave us these really big pillows.

541
00:36:22,714 --> 00:36:25,912
- What's your philosophy
on employee relations?
- That's a very tiny pillow.

542
00:36:25,984 --> 00:36:28,715
Great. It sounds like you
know what you're doing.

543
00:36:28,787 --> 00:36:31,347
<i>Greg.</i>

544
00:36:31,423 --> 00:36:34,154
- Can I have a word?
- Can it wait for the commercial, Marty?

545
00:36:34,225 --> 00:36:36,990
<i>Say hi to my friend Jimmy.</i>

546
00:36:38,496 --> 00:36:40,692
Pleasure.

547
00:36:40,765 --> 00:36:42,757
Your diagnostic trial...

548
00:36:42,834 --> 00:36:45,065
Seriously, commercial's
in about five minutes.

549
00:36:45,136 --> 00:36:48,072
- That's a dangerous game.
- Only if we're watching in the bathtub.

550
00:36:48,139 --> 00:36:52,270
I need to know exactly what
medications you were giving John Henry.

551
00:36:52,343 --> 00:36:55,404
Forget it. And if Foreman tells you
what John Henry used to be on...

552
00:36:55,480 --> 00:36:57,915
- You're gonna fire him?
- Nope.

553
00:36:57,982 --> 00:37:00,577
I'll make him live out every
day of his two-year contract.

554
00:37:00,652 --> 00:37:02,621
- Foreman asked to leave?
- Not yet.

555
00:37:02,687 --> 00:37:06,385
- But how do you know I made him— - You're
a polite twit, but you're not an idiot.

556
00:37:07,459 --> 00:37:10,657
I need to know what medications
you've taken him off of.

557
00:37:13,531 --> 00:37:16,524
Wait a second.
You're not an idiot.

558
00:37:18,970 --> 00:37:22,236
You need to know what
medications I've stopped...

559
00:37:22,307 --> 00:37:24,242
because...

560
00:37:26,911 --> 00:37:28,903
He's getting worse.

561
00:37:33,485 --> 00:37:35,818
Right now you still
work for me. Come on.

562
00:37:38,490 --> 00:37:40,482
No feeling. No wiggling.

563
00:37:40,558 --> 00:37:44,051
Bad news is John Henry's back where he
started. Good news is Hamilton looks bad.

564
00:37:44,129 --> 00:37:47,463
Yeah, it's not whether you win or
lose. It's whether the other guy loses.

565
00:37:47,532 --> 00:37:50,077
What was the first thing we put
him on? Steroids, for the pneumonia.

566
00:37:50,101 --> 00:37:52,764
Well, put him back on them. Give
him 24 hours. See what happens.

567
00:37:52,837 --> 00:37:55,830
His lungs aren't great. They might
cause another respiratory collapse.

568
00:37:55,907 --> 00:37:57,967
Sure hope not. I didn't
much like that lawyer.

569
00:37:58,042 --> 00:38:00,443
And get an M.R.I. He
already got one, and an M.R.A.

570
00:38:00,512 --> 00:38:02,913
Well, obviously something
is different now. Do it again.

571
00:38:02,981 --> 00:38:05,974
Chase, take care of the scan.
Cameron, put him on the steroids.

572
00:38:08,953 --> 00:38:10,945
We should probably talk, huh?

573
00:38:16,795 --> 00:38:19,355
Thin cuts. What levels?

574
00:38:19,430 --> 00:38:22,366
T-9 through the cauda
equina, same as the last time.

575
00:38:24,369 --> 00:38:27,271
You really think House would let
Foreman out of his contract? <i>He has to.</i>

576
00:38:27,338 --> 00:38:31,036
If he doesn't, he's telling Foreman
he needs him. House can't handle that.

577
00:38:37,348 --> 00:38:40,284
Oh, my God.

578
00:38:44,455 --> 00:38:46,447
I checked him out.

579
00:38:47,592 --> 00:38:50,756
He's a great doctor.

580
00:38:50,829 --> 00:38:54,561
- You think he's better than I am?
- This about your ego?

581
00:38:54,632 --> 00:38:56,828
Answer the question.

582
00:38:58,603 --> 00:39:03,007
It's not gonna change how I think about
myself. Might affect my opinion of you,

583
00:39:03,074 --> 00:39:05,839
but that shouldn't affect
your opinion of yourself.

584
00:39:06,711 --> 00:39:08,077
Now I'm getting confused.

585
00:39:08,146 --> 00:39:11,776
If you think he's a better doctor than
I am, then you should take the job.

586
00:39:11,850 --> 00:39:14,581
Otherwise, you should get
him to buy you two or three

587
00:39:14,605 --> 00:39:17,153
more nostalgic lunches
and then politely decline.

588
00:39:17,222 --> 00:39:20,420
It's that simple? I should just
ignore the mockery and abuse?

589
00:39:20,491 --> 00:39:23,620
- Oh, how do I abuse you?
- How do you not?

590
00:39:23,695 --> 00:39:26,426
- If I make a mistake— - I hold
you accountable. So what?

591
00:39:26,497 --> 00:39:29,568
Dr. Hamilton forgives.
He's capable of moving on.

592
00:39:29,592 --> 00:39:31,231
That is not what he does.

593
00:39:31,302 --> 00:39:34,329
I screwed up his case. He told
me— <i>He never said you were forgiven.</i>

594
00:39:34,405 --> 00:39:36,340
I was there. He said
it wasn't your fault.

595
00:39:36,407 --> 00:39:38,535
- So?
- So, it was.

596
00:39:38,610 --> 00:39:41,444
<i>You took a chance.
You did something great.</i>

597
00:39:41,512 --> 00:39:45,074
You were wrong, but it was still great.
You should feel great that it was great.

598
00:39:45,149 --> 00:39:47,128
<i>You should feel like
crap that it was wrong.</i>

599
00:39:47,152 --> 00:39:49,018
<i>That's the difference
between him and me.</i>

600
00:39:49,087 --> 00:39:51,647
He thinks you do your
job, and what will be will be.

601
00:39:51,723 --> 00:39:53,885
I think that what I do
and what you do matters.

602
00:39:56,160 --> 00:39:58,959
He sleeps better at
night. He shouldn't.

603
00:40:02,133 --> 00:40:05,467
- Arteriovenous malformation.
- Intradural. Compressing his spine.

604
00:40:07,705 --> 00:40:09,640
Causing his paralysis.

605
00:40:09,707 --> 00:40:12,438
How could Hamilton
have missed an A.V.M.?

606
00:40:12,510 --> 00:40:14,445
Well, we missed it too,

607
00:40:14,512 --> 00:40:16,640
'cause it wasn't there before.

608
00:40:16,714 --> 00:40:18,706
Are you saying it
just grew overnight?

609
00:40:18,783 --> 00:40:20,718
No.

610
00:40:20,785 --> 00:40:24,552
It was on the spine.
It wasn't on the M.R.I.

611
00:40:24,622 --> 00:40:28,718
- Same anatomic location.
- It's not there.

612
00:40:28,793 --> 00:40:31,991
- Well, what is there?
- Nothing.

613
00:40:32,063 --> 00:40:35,227
Or something that
looks like nothing.

614
00:40:37,235 --> 00:40:40,330
<i>- Background noise. Static.</i>
- Scar tissue? Inflammation?

615
00:40:40,405 --> 00:40:43,136
If it's inflammation, the
steroids would've shrunk it down.

616
00:40:44,442 --> 00:40:46,434
Revealing the A.V.M.,

617
00:40:46,511 --> 00:40:49,106
which has always been there,
hiding behind its own swelling.

618
00:40:49,180 --> 00:40:50,944
We remove that,
he'll walk again.

619
00:40:59,257 --> 00:41:02,750
<i>♪♪</i>

620
00:41:39,230 --> 00:41:42,132
Dr. House.

621
00:41:43,401 --> 00:41:46,337
Cora's meeting me
outside with the limo.

622
00:41:47,338 --> 00:41:50,001
I'm bein' discharged.

623
00:41:50,074 --> 00:41:52,236
Fifty bucks says I can
beat you to the curb.

624
00:41:52,310 --> 00:41:56,145
Thanks for stickin'
with the case.

625
00:41:56,214 --> 00:41:59,150
I can't do anything else.

626
00:42:00,385 --> 00:42:02,650
You're much more easily
amused when you can walk.

627
00:42:02,720 --> 00:42:04,780
How bizarre.

628
00:42:04,856 --> 00:42:07,189
I'm guessing that you
weren't exactly Mr. Sunshine...

629
00:42:07,258 --> 00:42:09,921
even before your
leg got messed up.

630
00:42:13,231 --> 00:42:15,166
I want you to have this.

631
00:42:24,942 --> 00:42:26,877
Wow.

632
00:42:26,944 --> 00:42:30,210
You can sell it if you want to.
Just promise me you won't play it.

633
00:42:35,386 --> 00:42:37,719
How many of those
pills you takin'?

634
00:42:39,490 --> 00:42:41,755
I'm in pain.

635
00:42:42,827 --> 00:42:44,819
Yes.

636
00:42:46,364 --> 00:42:48,424
Aren't we all?

637
00:42:50,168 --> 00:42:53,002
So, uh, where do you buy these
things? Do they have cane stores?

638
00:42:53,071 --> 00:42:56,473
Ah, don't worry about it. You'll be
jogging before you need a second one.

639
00:42:56,541 --> 00:42:58,635
See you tomorrow, <i>Eric.</i>

640
00:43:36,681 --> 00:43:37,910
That's some bad hat, Harry.
